                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p>Maen Llia <term>rejected monument</term> <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/">CPAT Regional Historic Environment Record</ref>: <idno type="HER">3225</idno></p>
                                    <material type="stone">Stone type unknown</material> 
                                    <objectType key="monument">Slab</objectType> 
                                    <dimensions unit="m" source="MAC1945">
                                        <height>3.40</height>
                                        <width>2.54</width>
                                        <depth>0.30</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition>Neither the ogham or roman-letter inscription is visible on the stone today. Macalister (1945, 329) states that he detected traces of both ogham and roman letters upon the stone but that <q>the lettering—if it be lettering—is reduced practically to evanescence</q>. </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">According to Macalister (1922, 202), the broad face of the stone which is turned towards the road is incised with both an ogham and roman-letter inscription. The ogham inscription occupied the south angle of the stone, presumably reading upwards, and the <q>surviving letters are just above the angle in the edge of the stone</q> (Macalister 1945, 330). The roman-letter inscription consists of two lines, reading top downwards, but not vertical. Instead the two lines are <q>more or less parallel with the sinister edge below the angle just mentioned</q> (Macalister 1945, 330). 
</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>There is no evidence to indicate how the inscriptions might have been carved, so the execution technique remains <rs type="execution" key="other">unknown</rs>. 
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origPlace><placeName type="parish">Ystradfellte</placeName>, <placeName type="county">Brecknockshire (<foreign xml:lang="cy"><ref target="https://historicplacenames.rcahmw.gov.uk/placenames/recordedname/6d25abb9-918e-4aca-98ce-9c921395aec5">Brycheiniog</ref></foreign>)</placeName>, <placeName type="country">Wales</placeName>
                                <geo>51.860975, -3.563928</geo> </origPlace>
                            <origDate/>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance type="found">The stone stands on moorland at 430 m above ordnance datum at the head of the pass between Fan Llia and Fan Nedd, near the spring source of the little river Llia. Macalister (1922, 202) was the first to suggest the presence of ogham and roman-letter inscriptions. 
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed">In situ.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
