            <div type="apparatus">
                <app n="1">
                    <note>Macalister (1945, 330) provided the following tentative reading:</note>
                    <rdg>Ogham: VASSO(G?)</rdg>
                    <rdg><lb n="1"/>Roman: ROVEVI
                    <lb n="2"/>S....SOVI</rdg>
                </app>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>No translation is offered for either inscription</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Redknapp and Lewis (2007, 547) maintain that the evidence for the ogham and roman-letter inscriptions is <q>unconvincing</q> and list the stone as a 'Rejected monument'. According to Redknap and Lewis (2007, 547), <q>the assumption must be that the stone is prehistoric: certainly the kinds of legend frequently associated with such stones seem to have accumulated around it. One claims that whenever a cock crows, the stone moves off to drink in the river Nedd; in another the stone visits the river Mellte on Midsummer morning</q> (Grinsell 1976, 59).
                </p>
            </div>
